Are Kids in School Ready for The Next School Year?¶

It can be hard tor a kid to know if they're ready to move on to the next grade, it's a step forward and a lot of kids can struggle with the new concepts introduced to them, especially in the jump from Middle School to High School. Standardized tests are one way of knowing if a kid is ready, the Specialized High School Admissions Test (SHSAT) is used in New York. PASSNYC, a non-profit organization in New York is trying to help understand what kids in what schools are in the most need of extra resources to help them feel more prepared for the future.

Scores on the SHSAT:

  • 1: Insufficient
  • 2: Partial but insufficient
  • 3: Sufficient
  • 4: More than sufficient

This dataset only catalogs if a student has scored a 4, to be able to represent how many students are truly ready for the next grade.

Dataset¶

There is a lot of information in the dataset provided by PASSNYC.

  • Information about a School's location
  • Grades the School teaches
  • Economic Need Index of School
  • Estimate of School Income
  • Ethnicity distribution at a school
  • Metrics and whether or not the school is reaching their Targets
  • Average Math / ELA proficiency of students
  • Scores of students separated by Grades and Ethnicity
  • And more

Given this information we can try to come up with some conclusions to help us figure out what Schools are in the most need of funding.

The Formula¶

The way I'm going to be determining what Schools are most in need is by creating a weighted formula off of standardized values from important columns.

That is to say for every column that has a noticeable affect on the scores of students on exams, I will standardize the data to be between 0 and 1 and then multiplied it by a given weight value for how important I think that metric is in determining how in need of help a School is. So the most an important column can effect this Score is by adding 1 to the value, and the least it can affect the score is by adding 0. Once I have a total score I will standardize the Score value to be between 0 and a 100. A score of 100 will mean that that is the School that scored the highest on my In Need scale, and the school that scores a 0 will be the least In Need.

For any data that I have grouped by like this data by District, the way I will add the information to the weighted formula is by converting the continuous data to a categorical bin that is automatically sorted into 'lowest, low, medium and high', merge that with the original dataset and give a score based on what bin that district landed in.

Other Data About New York¶

Based on the open datasets provided by Kaggle about New York there were hundreds of datasets to choose from to see if there would be any correlation between the brought in data and the original data

Grocery Stores¶

I wanted to see if any area in New York would correspond to a food desert so I found a dataset that contained a list of grocery stores within new york and counted the number of Grocery Stores available within that zip code. This is the list of Grocery Stores in NYC

In [91]:
data.simple_scatter(['Grocery Store Count', 'Total 4 %'], reg_line=True,
                   title = 'Number of Local Grocery Stores and Proportion of 4s Scored')

There was no correlation between the number of local grocery stores and the scores on the SHSAT.









Public Transit¶

I was also curious about how the availability of public transit and if it affected scores on the SHSAT. This is a list of Metro stations in NYC.. I took the co-ordinates for all the entrances to the stations and computed the shortest distance between a school and a station measured in miles.

This is a Euclidean Distance between a given school and the closest Metro station, so it's meant to be more of a measurement of how close to public transit the school is and not a measurement of travel distance

In [92]:
data.simple_scatter(['Closest Metro Station', 'Total 4 %'], reg_line=True,
                   title = 'Distance To Metro Station and Proportion of 4s Scored')

Again, there was no correlation between the distance to the closest metro station and scoring on the SHSAT









Car Safety¶

This is a dataset about car crashes in NYC. I used this dataset as a measurement of how safe the roads are in NYC near these schools. Zip Codes were only tracked in this dataset if someone was injured in the car crash, meaning that these are only what can be considered moderate to severe car accidents.

In [93]:
data.simple_scatter(['Car Crash Count', 'Total 4 %'], reg_line=True,
                   title = 'Number of Car Crashes and Proportion of 4s Scored')

And again, there doesn't seem to be a correlation between Car Safety in areas around the Schools and scores on the SHSAT

This means that none of the merged in data has a strong enough correlation to be added to the In Need Scores weighted formula.

Conclusion¶

Looking at all the possible variables of the dataset with 1272 different Schools I created a weighted formula to score Schools based on different factors correlated with the scores on the SHSAT. I decided on these weights based on how much I determined they would affect the scores on the SHSAT, but I believe in the method that I used for determining the score.

What I belive could have helped me in the accuracy of assigning weights to different variables would be more domain knowledge about the subject. I have never worked in education before and it's possible that I could have made wrong assumptions about the strength of correlations given the dataset and any inherit biases that may have been within the data collected.

Things I would have liked to explore if time wasn't a factor:

  • A description for each school describing how their score was calculated, as in, which weighted scores scored the highest and lowest
  • Other types of visualization
  • More efficient methods in Classes that I wrote. Many solutions were not optimized beyond the sake of organization into smaller functions. I know many for loops could be replaced with vectorized solutions using Numpy Arrays for greater efficiencies.
  • More research into the values I chose for the weighted function









FIN¶
